The walls were talking again.

It was early morning --- so early Richard hadn't even left for the Watchtower yet. Ben would have liked to sleep in when he had nothing to do, but months of waking up before dawn had demented his sleep cycle into thinking that was normal, even with no alarm. Now he was kneeling to hear a tinny speaker while trying to watch the sunrise as best he could.

"Hello?" Richard's tone indicated it wasn't the first time he'd asked.

He was answered by a grunt and a drawn-out silence before a familiar scratchy voice asked, "Ready?"

"Yes." Richard still didn't sound authoritative, speaking in surprisingly hesitant tones. Ben would have laughed if laughing at Richard hadn't been driven out of him long ago.

"How long?" his father continued.

"Five minutes at most. They're on their way now." Another pause. "You're sure you're prepared."

"Without a doubt."

"Don't let anyone in or out of the building. Lock the doors. You'll be fine."

Richard went quiet, seeming to consider that. "What guarantee do I have?"

"Oh, god, not this again. You have my word."

Though his father actually chuckled, Ben could tell it didn't come from a place of confidence. "I have your word?" Richard asked, sarcastically.

"Yeah. And you also have the common sense that says if you let anyone outside, they might get shot. That'll have to be good enough for you."

"Don't kill anyone."

"Not if we can help it. And Richard?"

"What?"

"Check your phone lines." And the man hung up.



