The scene was settling. The paramedics, wearing masks, had come and gone with the victims, and now there was no one in sight.

Ben had already rid himself of everything he'd eaten in the past day and a half when the door opened, and one of the housekeepers entered. He looked similarly green in the face, but he brought with him a handful of bottles and a strange-looking device that Ben quickly learned was a massive diffuser. He watched, still nauseated to the point of delirium, as a bottle was loaded in and the smell of oranges filled the room. It wasn't enough to drown out the putrid stench that seemed to coat everything, but rotting flesh with oranges was decidedly better than rotting flesh, and he didn't complain.

Richard opened the door a few minutes later to ask if Ben was okay before closing it loudly and marching back off to his office. If Ben didn't know better, he would have said his father was irate. But that had to be panic, not anger. He had to just be reading it wrong.

He'd disconnected the wires. He knew he'd hear plenty if he plugged them back in, but he couldn't risk being heard, not now.

Still. If he was going to be grounded for two weeks, he wasn't about to sit quietly while his father somehow knew about an explosion --- and this godforsaken smell --- and failed to stop it.

He was going to learn all there was to know.



